{
  "texts": [
    "Choosing an appropriate sub-image size is crucial, as selecting smaller sizes could lead to missing the CAF peak, while larger sizes could result in multiple peaks and increased computational complexity.The sliding approach can be seen as analogous to the convolutional layers utilized in a CNN.",
    "In this method, the CAF is scanned in smaller windows with a stride of one cell.",
    "These windows can include both the primary signal peak and any spoofed signals.",
    "Notably, these peaks exhibit correlations in both the delay and Doppler domains, which can be utilized by the NN classifier, as opposed to random noise-generated peaks.To train the NN-based classifier, the dataset generated comprised of snapshots with either spoofed signals and signal-plus-noise ( H 1) or signal-plus-noise ( H 0), which were then divided into sub-images as illustrated in Fig. 2.",
    "These types of snapshots were used as input for the NN training."
  ]
}